I guess when I object to some versions of the "dialectic" it's on the basis of 'better than usual clunky but still not very complex understandings of times'. *some versions* as what do I know. + "materialism" so grounded in the social (often a c19th version) it becomes inflexible

And I'd add in I'd go with significant feedback loops (well much more complex than "loops") are found more in brain-world relations (taken ecologically multiply) than in supposed mind-body relations. Per Whitehead but also Georg Northoff.

With all the usual caveats re neuro (although I think Barrett's pretty great, even if I don't go with some of her other framings perhaps at times). I also have to say I'm reading this along with Harries-Jones on bioentropy, and others.

I suspect a lot of this applies to more general abstract-life settings, including philosophy perhaps but this across the ongoing generation of novelty and continuation of past abstract-life involvements in everyday life, professional/political settings, etc.

Yet that refusal is arguably part of a general ecology of mind problem in itself. The idea that "our activism". set in our own specific participation in broader complex ecologies, is somehow "the way" can become pretty rigid if bioentropically limited, not open to variation.

& of course those trying to make change happen (or making it happen) are immersed in the same, for one thing in terms of how they think/feel the potential for change, models, theories etc. Another reason why change doesn't (or does) happen, if a reason refused for the most part.

One way to think about it:For every ton of fossil CO2 emission you choose not to cause, you add 1% to the carbon budgets of all your descendants. Think about that for the next flight or any carbon intensive economic activity you decide to spend your money on.
And then we haven't even started to address a fair sharing of the remaining emission-budgets.https://t.co/iUn6cvzLNq https://t.co/1NJ5oHuW4a

You might argue that "we" at some point will suck the CO2 back out from the atmosphere - "refilling our budgets". "We" means our children, and our children's children etc. A lot will already be on their plate to solve.
These are not like budgets that are renewed every generation or year. No, these are emission-budgets that many generations in the future also are constrained by.

The Express' actual reaction nowadays would be more like, 'DIANA SAYS: Ignore the NANNY STATE, enjoy the HEAT, claims top medium'.

The most unrealistic thing about the film is that much of the action takes place in the newsroom of the Daily Express, which is at the forefront of investigating and reporting on the unfolding disaster.

Some images were strongly reminiscent of the recent summer heatwave. A newspaper with the headline 'Hottest it's ever been', lying on the grass next to people cheerfully sunbathing, transitioning to scenes of heaths and woods on fire.

In historical context, it's an anti-nuclear film; the climatic shifts humanity endures are caused by ill-advised bomb tests. But large swathes of the story are effective analogues for fossil-fuel-driven global warming.
